#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:1
msgid ""
"---\n"
"title: \"Workshop Introductions\"\n"
"block: \"The Carpentries\"\n"
"teaching: 10\n"
"exercises: 30\n"
"questions:\n"
"- \"How do you actually start a workshop?\"\n"
"objectives:\n"
"- \"Create an outline of important topics to cover in an introduction.\"\n"
"- \"Describe three ways to start workshop participants talking to each other.\"\n"
"- \"Receive one piece of feedback on your own introduction\"\n"
"keypoints:\n"
"- \"A planned introduction is a helpful tool in setting the workshop environment.\"  \n"
"- \"Introductions should both include practical information and start building relationships.\"  \n"
"---"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:17
msgid ""
"One of the most important things that you can do as an instructor is to\n"
"set the workshop environment from the beginning.  One way to do this\n"
"is by having a well-planned introduction.  This episode discusses the\n"
"value of setting the environment from the beginning and some of the\n"
"components that go into an effective introduction, and includes time to\n"
"practice giving part of a workshop introduction."
msgstr ""

# header
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:24
msgid "## Setting the Workshop Environment"
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:26
msgid "> ## Your Academic Past"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:27
msgid ""
">\n"
"> Think back to courses or workshops you really liked or didn't like.\n"
"> - How did those courses start?\n"
"> - Were you confident in the instructors abilities?\n"
"> - Did you feel like they were enthusiastic about the course and invested in you?\n"
"> - Was it clear what you were going to be learning?\n"
"> - Were you excited about the material?\n"
"> - Did you leave that first day thinking the instructor was uninterested, that you weren't the learners they wanted to\n"
"be teaching or you had no idea what the course was supposed to be about?"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:38
msgid ""
"Your impression on the first day of a course probably matched that of the rest of\n"
"the course. Introductions set the tone for the workshop and the path for learning."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:41
msgid ""
"Introductions are particularly important when we have just two days. Also,\n"
"in Carpentry workshops we're teaching not only a set of skills, but also\n"
"trying to give learners the confidence to become self-directed learners. Learners\n"
"should leave feeling excited and empowered. It's up to you as an instructor to empower\n"
"your learners, so it's important\n"
"to set a positive and welcoming environment for the workshop."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:48
msgid ""
"Having a planned introduction, also helps you be less nervous. Having a planned introduction\n"
"helps get you started. Even in the face of\n"
"early technical issues  (which is common at the start of a workshop), you can have a chance to reset with something\n"
"you're comfortable and ready for."
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:53
msgid "> ## What's in an Introduction?"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:54
msgid ""
">\n"
"> Get into small groups (3-4 people) and discuss these questions for 10 minutes.  \n"
"> Take notes on your answers -- we'll combine them later.  \n"
">\n"
"> 1. What do you hope to accomplish in a workshop introduction?\n"
"> 2. What information do you need to include in an introduction to accomplish these goals?\n"
">\n"
"> After 5 minutes, come together, and combine ideas as a large group.  \n"
">\n"
"> Finally, compare your ideas with the list of topics below.  Did you miss anything?  \n"
"> Did you come up with something that's not listed below?  \n"
">\n"
"> Optional question: what did you (the leader) do or not do in your introduction to the session?"
msgstr ""

