# header
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:95
msgid "### 1. Set Positive First Impressions"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:97
msgid ""
"First impressions can be long-lasting. Before you even start teaching, your learners\n"
"will have already made some decisions about you, so it is important to\n"
"understand what those impressions are based on and how to manage them."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:101
msgid ""
"**Your attire.** Research shows that clothing affects the\n"
"judgments people make, including credibility,\n"
"likability, dominance, kindness, and empathy (Raiscot, 1986; Morris et\n"
"al., 1996). More formal attire communicates expertise and confidence.\n"
"Less formal attire communicates approachability. Usually, it is easier\n"
"to relax from a more formal impression into a more relaxed one than the\n"
"other way around. These considerations are likely to be particularly\n"
"relevant for young instructors who are concerned about establishing\n"
"themselves as authoritative."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:111
msgid ""
"**The physical environment**. Learners can make decisions about what\n"
"kind of course yours will be by the way the chairs are arranged. Rows\n"
"signify a more formal environment, while circles or U-shapes imply a\n"
"more informal atmosphere, with higher expectations of learner\n"
"participation."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:117
msgid ""
"**Your use of the few minutes before class.** Greeting the learners as\n"
"they enter the classroom communicates approachability. Frantically\n"
"arriving right on time or late communicates disorganization."
msgstr ""

# header
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:121
msgid "### 2. Introduce Yourself Effectively"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:123
msgid ""
"Your introduction should be succinct, but make sure to cover certain\n"
"key areas. These questions should help you decide what to say:"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:126
msgid ""
"**What characteristics do you want to convey about yourself?** You probably want the learners to get a sense of your\n"
"qualifications, how formal/informal you want\n"
"to be, and how available you will be to the learners. You want to\n"
"demonstrate that you're qualified, but that you share the same\n"
"challenges as the learners, so you remain accessible."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:132
msgid ""
"**What will you need to say to convey those characteristics?**\n"
"Consider talking about your research and computational interests as\n"
"they relate to the workshop, in order to establish yourself as an\n"
"authority, and to make the workshop more relevant."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:137
msgid ""
"**Why are you teaching a Carpentries workshop?**\n"
"Why are you an instructor? What's motivating you to be there today? One\n"
"reason might be that you took a workshop and saw how valuable these\n"
"skills were in your own work and wanted to share this information with\n"
"others. Convey your enthusiasm for being there."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:143
msgid ""
"**What should you be careful not to say?** Learners do not need to\n"
"know everything about you. In particular, it is not helpful to say\n"
"you've never taught the course before, or that it is your least\n"
"favorite course to teach, or to disclose any irrelevant personal\n"
"information that can undermine you in the eyes of your learners."
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:149
msgid "> ## Introductions for Everyone"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:150
msgid ""
">\n"
"> If you're teaching a typical Carpentries workshop, then you're\n"
"> probably not teaching alone!  After introducing yourself, make\n"
"> sure that you give everyone involved in the workshop - instructors,\n"
"> helpers, organizers - a chance to introduce themselves as well.\n"
">\n"
"> If you're the workshop organizer, this can also be a good time\n"
"> to thank volunteers who are instructing or helping."
msgstr ""

# header
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:160
msgid "### 3. Clarify Learning Objectives and Your Expectations"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:162
msgid ""
"This is probably the most important step. Clearly laying out\n"
"expectations orients learners towards what you expect from them,\n"
"and helps them use their time productively."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:166
msgid ""
"**Describe the prerequisites** so learners will know what information\n"
"you are assuming they already know. For Data Carpentry no prior\n"
"computational experience is required. Expectations vary for Software\n"
"Carpentry and Library Carpentry workshops. Convey what your expectations are."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:171
msgid "**Highlight main aspects of the schedule.**"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:173
msgid ""
"**Communicate the workshop structure** so the learners will\n"
"understand the decisions that have been made in designing the workshop.\n"
"Make sure to highlight\n"
"the learning objectives and the hands-on instructional strategies we use and\n"
"the workshop policies."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:179
msgid ""
"**Clarify workshop roles.** Explain who is doing what at the workshop and\n"
"what learners can expect from the workshop leaders.  If you haven't already\n"
"introduced helpers or other workshop leaders, make sure to do so.  "
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:183
msgid ""
"**Explain your expectations** for learner behavior including expectations\n"
"around:"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:186
msgid ""
"- [Code of "
"Conduct](https://docs.carpentries.org/topic_folders/policies/index_coc.html)"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:187
msgid "- ways to ask for help"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:188
msgid "- ways to give instructors feedback"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:190
msgid "**Communicate your commitment** to the learners' learning experience."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:192
msgid ""
"**Share some advice for success** in your course. Let learners\n"
"know you are confident in their success as long as they put in\n"
"the required effort."
msgstr ""

# header
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:196
msgid "### 4. Help Learners Learn About Each Other"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:198
msgid ""
"The classroom is a social environment, so it is helpful to start the\n"
"social dynamics in a productive way."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:201
msgid ""
"Icebreakers raise the energy levels and get learners comfortable so\n"
"that they will be ready to work in groups or dialogue with each other.  "
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:204
msgid "> ## Example Icebreaker"
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:205
msgid "> Here is one example of an icebreaker you can use:  "
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:206
msgid "> Have everyone turn to a partner and introduce themselves with their"
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:207
msgid "> name, one word about their research 'microbes', 'dogs', 'vectors',"
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:208
msgid "> 'stars' and a thing they're proud of that they made."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:211
msgid "Head here for [more examples of Icebreakers][icebreakers].  "
msgstr ""

# header
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:213
msgid "### 5. Set the Tone for the Workshop"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:215
msgid ""
"The way you engage learners at the beginning sends powerful messages\n"
"about the level of involvement and interaction you expect from them."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:218
msgid ""
"Since these workshops are hands-on don't spend a lot of the time at\n"
"the beginning lecturing. Get to introductions and interactions\n"
"right away. You don't want learners to think they just have to listen\n"
"in the course."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:223
msgid ""
"Also establish a culture of feedback. Let learners know you are\n"
"interested in how they experience the course and in any suggestions\n"
"they have. Let them know they should feel free to give you constructive\n"
"feedback, even\n"
"anonymously. They can do this in particular with minute cards. You\n"
"might not adopt every suggestion they have but you will listen and\n"
"consider them. This starts to create a partnership in learning."
msgstr ""

# header
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:231
msgid "### 6. Collect Baseline Data on Learners' Knowledge and Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:233
msgid ""
"You will already have information on their skill level from the\n"
"pre-assessment survey.\n"
"Before starting your workshop, decide what to do about different/inadequate prior knowledge.  If this\n"
"is a workshop where a certain knowledge is required (such as an\n"
"advertised advanced workshop), decide in advance how you will handle a\n"
"range of skill sets.  You might tell them they cannot take the\n"
"workshop, or that they must work through certain sections on their\n"
"own."
msgstr ""

# header
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:242
msgid "### 7. Whet Learners' Appetites for Workshop Content"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:244
msgid ""
"They're already at the workshop, so it might seem unnecessary to\n"
"motivate them to be there, but it is a great chance to stimulate\n"
"interest about the workshop and to activate relevant prior knowledge\n"
"learners have about the material."
msgstr ""

# header
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:249
msgid "### 8. Inform Learners of Logistics"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:251
msgid ""
"Let them know about any logistics for the days - lunch times, breaks,\n"
"accessibility, etc."
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:254
msgid "> ## Practice Your Introduction"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/23-introductions.md:255
msgid ""
">\n"
"> Imagine you have completed instructor training and you are about to teach a full lesson around the material you have been practicing teaching today.\n"
">\n"
"> 1. Write out some notes, covering some of the topics described above:\n"
"> \t1.  Introduce yourself effectively\n"
"> \t1.  Clarify learning objectives and expectations\n"
"> \t1.  Set the tone for the workshop\n"
"> 2. Return to your groups of 2 or 3 and each give 2 minutes of your introduction. (5-6 min)\n"
"> 3. After each introduction, provide 2-3 minutes of feedback.  \n"
">\n"
"> This exercise will take 15-25 minutes depending on whether time is included for feedback or not.  "
msgstr ""

